div.h1: ISR Stub Assembly Stack State Before/After Each Instruction
div.p: isr_common_stub execution trace privilege-change path (SS/ESP present)

g.text: Step 0 CPU Hardware Pushes Interrupt Frame
Step 2 pusha (saves EAX ECX EDX EBX ESP EBP ESI EDI)
Step 3 Push Segment Registers (push ds / es / fs / gs)
Step 4 CRITICAL: Reload Kernel Data Segments
Step 5 push esp (pass interrupt_frame_t* to C handler)
Step 6 C Handler Returns; Restore Begins
Step 7 iretd Complete: User Process Resumed at Ring 3

div.p: Trigger: IRQ or exception fires while ring-3 code runs. CPU reads TSS.ESP0 switches to kernel stack. Pushes 5 words automatically (privilege-change path).
ISR_ERR skips the fake push CPU already pushed the real error code. Both paths now have identical stack layout entering isr_common_stub.
pusha push order (EAX first EAX at highest address in block): Stack lowhigh after pusha: EDI ESI EBP esp_dummy EBX EDX ECX EAX This matches interrupt_frame_t field order exactly.

text.tspan: ; save current DS (may be 0x23 if from ring-3)
; save current DS (may be 0x23 if from ring-3)

div.p: Without this step the kernel faults immediately. If DS still holds 0x23 (user-mode selector, DPL=3), the next kernel memory access (e.g., reading interrupt_dispatch function pointer) checks DPL: CPL=0 > DPL=3 allowed, but the segment limit and base from the user descriptor are wrong for kernel virtual addresses General Protection Fault (#GP, vector 13) before any C code runs.

g.text: mov ax, 0x10 ; kernel data selector (GDT[2], DPL=0)
mov ds, ax ; replaces user DS with kernel DS
; SS is already 0x10 (CPU set it from TSS.SS0 on privilege change)

text.tspan: ; replaces user DS with kernel DS

div.p: Stack unchanged no push/pop here. Only CPU segment-descriptor cache registers (DS, ES, FS, GS) change. ESP stays at ESP 76.

text.tspan: ; argument: pointer to interrupt_frame_t on stack
; argument: pointer to interrupt_frame_t on stack

div.p: esp pushed before the call so the C function receives a pointer to the GS field (lowest address of the saved frame). interrupt_frame_t* field gs sits at offset 0 from this pointer.

g.text: add esp, 4 ; discard pushed frame ptr (cdecl cleanup)

text.tspan: ; restore segment registers (reverse of push order)

g.text: iretd ; restore EIP, CS, EFLAGS [, ESP, SS] from CPU-saved block

text.tspan: ; restore segment registers (reverse of push order)

div.p: add esp, 8 is essential without it iretd pops err_code as EIP and int_no as CS, jumping to a garbage address. iretd detects CS.RPL=3 also pops ESP and SS full ring-3 restore.
CPU pops from kernel stack (now back at ESP 20):

ul.li: CS 0x1B (ring-3 code, RPL=3) privilege level drops to 3
ESP user_esp (switches back to user stack)

SS 0x23 (user stack segment) Kernel stack is fully unwound to ESP. All general-purpose and segment registers restored to pre-interrupt values. User process continues with zero visible evidence of the interrupt.
